250
00:14:08.624 --> 00:14:10.344
all of the other circumstances as well.

251
00:14:11.844 --> 00:14:15.824
It seems the bill will allow police to shut down any area, remove

252
00:14:15.884 --> 00:14:19.364
the people for a number of reasons, including they believe that public

253
00:14:20.443 --> 00:14:24.304
disorder is imminent, or that a group of people may be expected

254
00:14:24.344 --> 00:14:26.504
to cause excessive noise from a vehicle.

255
00:14:27.544 --> 00:14:30.844
Now, these aren't the totality of the reasons listed, but I've picked out these

256
00:14:31.004 --> 00:14:34.904
because firstly, they deal with things that haven't actually happened at the time

257
00:14:34.914 --> 00:14:35.684
the order was made.

258
00:14:36.573 --> 00:14:39.244
As someone who believes that people should be allowed to go about their lives

259
00:14:39.284 --> 00:14:42.103
freely as much as possible, this seems very wrong to me.

260
00:14:43.484 --> 00:14:47.084
Now we not only have to avoid breaking the law, we also have to make sure we don't

261
00:14:47.124 --> 00:14:48.884
give the impression that we might break the law.

262
00:14:50.064 --> 00:14:54.004
The second reason I've picked them out is that those descriptions also apply to

263
00:14:54.044 --> 00:14:55.444
political protest.

264
00:14:56.264 --> 00:14:59.964
Normal political protest in a democracy is often loud, at least

265
00:15:00.044 --> 00:15:03.964
somewhat disorderly, and sometimes involves people using loudspeakers or

266
00:15:04.024 --> 00:15:05.744
music systems mounted on vehicles.

267
00:15:06.764 --> 00:15:10.464
It seems to me the powers in this bill will be able to use to shut down political

268
00:15:10.524 --> 00:15:14.424
demonstrations, order people to disperse, and arrest them if

269
00:15:14.464 --> 00:15:18.444
they refuse or try to return. And this is a big problem for a rights-respecting

270
00:15:18.484 --> 00:15:19.164
democracy.

271
00:15:20.284 --> 00:15:23.464
Now, to finish off, I want to talk about what these two parts have in common,

272
00:15:24.404 --> 00:15:27.624
and what it is is that there are no meaningful

273
00:15:27.764 --> 00:15:31.264
restrictions on the use of these powers. There's no exceptions.

274
00:15:31.504 --> 00:15:35.424
There's no oversight. There's no approval process or requirement for a

275
00:15:35.484 --> 00:15:37.924
senior officer to be involved. There's no appeal.

276
00:15:38.424 --> 00:15:39.764
There are really no limits.

277
00:15:40.664 --> 00:15:44.474
The bill embodies a view that the police will never misuse or abuse their

278
00:15:44.564 --> 00:15:48.484
powers, that every police officer and employee, because it covers employees

279
00:15:48.524 --> 00:15:52.444
as well, will always do the right thing, that we don't need to limit how

280
00:15:52.464 --> 00:15:53.484
police powers are used.

281
00:15:54.314 --> 00:15:57.284
I believe this is a very dangerous view. Police are human.

282
00:15:57.304 --> 00:15:59.844
They make mistakes. They exhibit bias.

283
00:15:59.853 --> 00:16:02.184
Some of them are unfortunately corrupt.

284
00:16:02.204 --> 00:16:06.104
And for one obvious and exhaustively documented example, police

285
00:16:06.384 --> 00:16:09.704
statistics and reports clearly show they're biased against Māori.

286
00:16:11.024 --> 00:16:14.964
A society that enacts laws that the police are always right is going down a very

287
00:16:15.004 --> 00:16:18.704
dangerous path towards authoritarianism, and that's why I say it's a

288
00:16:18.744 --> 00:16:22.434
radical bill. It's a radical extension of police powers, and it's

289
00:16:22.584 --> 00:16:24.824
radical in the way that it assumes that police can do no wrong.

290
00:16:25.544 --> 00:16:27.763
I believe that we should not pass it in its current form.

291
00:16:28.524 --> 00:16:31.304
And that's not to say the purpose of the bill is inherently wrong.

292
00:16:31.944 --> 00:16:35.804
I believe there is room to better codify how, when, where, and

293
00:16:35.844 --> 00:16:38.024
why police can record audio and video.

294
00:16:38.864 --> 00:16:41.824
I believe there may be room to give police the ability to close areas where

295
00:16:41.944 --> 00:16:43.304
large-scale lawlessness is happening.

296
00:16:44.384 --> 00:16:47.824
But these purposes have to be taken seriously in the context of a

297
00:16:47.844 --> 00:16:50.604
rights-respecting democratic society that values freedom,

298
00:16:51.564 --> 00:16:54.244
which is a version of Aotearoa that I'd like to live in.

299
00:16:54.934 --> 00:16:58.484
They need proper consideration of how we can let police do their

300
00:16:58.524 --> 00:17:02.084
job while still protecting our rights, not this carte blanche

301
00:17:02.744 --> 00:17:03.924
do what you want license.

302
00:17:04.874 --> 00:17:07.424
I recommend you send this bill back for a substantial rewrite.

303
00:17:07.964 --> 00:17:10.684
If you don't, please consider some of the suggestions we made in our written

304
00:17:10.724 --> 00:17:14.124
submission. Thank you for your time. I'm happy to answer any questions.

305
00:17:14.424 --> 00:17:18.285
Thank you, Thomas. You have got still some time, and there is a question

306
00:17:18.325 --> 00:17:21.424
from Dan Rosewarne. So if you- Yeah. Thank you. Thank you, Thomas.

307
00:17:21.884 --> 00:17:25.724
Just a question around recommendation two of your submission, where you

308
00:17:25.844 --> 00:17:29.704
suggest rewording the new Section 45A, and

309
00:17:29.724 --> 00:17:33.344
it's got, "Police constables may make recordings in public without

310
00:17:33.444 --> 00:17:37.044
warrant only when there is a reason to believe that there'll be use of

311
00:17:37.104 --> 00:17:40.944
force or when violent or aggressive behavior is

312
00:17:41.004 --> 00:17:44.884
anticipated or displayed." My question is, isn't that

313
00:17:44.964 --> 00:17:48.904
still quite broad? Because the reason I ask is the way I read it, it would

314
00:17:49.004 --> 00:17:52.964
still allow everyday interactions to be recorded just in

315
00:17:53.024 --> 00:17:56.804
case something becomes useful later, which is one of your concerns, and I'm just

316
00:17:56.824 --> 00:17:59.384
wondering if you had any further thoughts on that at all.

317
00:18:00.644 --> 00:18:03.824
I think that was partly inspired by some of the work we're reading about body

318
00:18:03.884 --> 00:18:06.604
cameras, and I think it's actually meant to be limiting it to that.

319
00:18:07.114 --> 00:18:09.364
That may be slightly overly restrictive, to be honest.

320
00:18:10.004 --> 00:18:12.644
I think it might be more than we'd say we'd want to go.

321
00:18:13.004 --> 00:18:16.948
But it's coming from that view of that-We do want to be able

322
00:18:16.968 --> 00:18:20.728
to set limits and reasons and requirements for

323
00:18:20.828 --> 00:18:24.288
when these things are being recorded, when recording is happening.

324
00:18:24.628 --> 00:18:27.068
And I think that's really the most important point to take out of that.

325
00:18:28.148 --> 00:18:30.368
We also have another question from Carl Bates.

326
00:18:31.068 --> 00:18:35.028
Thanks very much, Chair. Accepting, Thomas, that part of what you're

327
00:18:35.068 --> 00:18:38.528
referring to about being able to have

328
00:18:38.568 --> 00:18:42.088
surveillance into closed spaces, parking that for a moment, in

329
00:18:42.128 --> 00:18:46.028
relation to your concerns around surveillance in open spaces,

330
00:18:46.108 --> 00:18:49.288
particularly around digital videoing and the like,

331
00:18:50.248 --> 00:18:53.408
where we live in a world where someone could be standing there and videoing the

332
00:18:53.468 --> 00:18:54.578
whole thing anyway-

333
00:18:55.068 --> 00:18:55.218
Mm-hmm

334
00:18:55.428 --> 00:18:58.308
... why is it such a concern that the police may,

335
00:18:59.768 --> 00:19:03.368
under this act, have the ability to

336
00:19:03.488 --> 00:19:04.598
also video that

337
00:19:05.628 --> 00:19:09.188
in a scenario where that could then be used later as evidence?

338
00:19:09.388 --> 00:19:09.888
Mm-hmm. Yep.

339
00:19:10.968 --> 00:19:11.828
I think the thing is that

340
00:19:13.148 --> 00:19:17.048
there is a power imbalance there. If a normal person is videoing me doing

341
00:19:17.688 --> 00:19:20.168
something, it's an equal power balance.

342
00:19:20.487 --> 00:19:24.368
When the police do things, they are acting with the power of the state,

343
00:19:25.548 --> 00:19:29.188
and it's intimidating. One of the examples I give is that

344
00:19:30.248 --> 00:19:31.108
talking to people who are at

345
00:19:32.048 --> 00:19:35.408
protests, this is actually a few years ago now, and they were saying that the

346
00:19:35.428 --> 00:19:39.148
police at these political protests standing back

347
00:19:39.528 --> 00:19:43.408
using long-lens cameras to zoom in and take

348
00:19:43.448 --> 00:19:47.118
photos of everyone there. And they found that intimidating,

349
00:19:47.548 --> 00:19:50.528
and it actually made them feel that they didn't want to turn up at future political

350
00:19:50.568 --> 00:19:53.368
protests. So it was discouraging their political participation.

351
00:19:53.968 --> 00:19:57.748
Now you can say, "Okay, but journalists might have been doing that too." And the

352
00:19:57.828 --> 00:20:01.478
answer is that the people would not have been nervous about journalists doing

353
00:20:01.528 --> 00:20:05.378
it. It was the fact that the state was doing it that caused the

354
00:20:05.408 --> 00:20:05.788
issue.

355
00:20:07.128 --> 00:20:08.828
And that applies across all these things.

356
00:20:08.868 --> 00:20:11.568
The actual rules we come up with,

357
00:20:12.408 --> 00:20:15.348
I've got opinions on what some of those should be and so on, but

358
00:20:15.368 --> 00:20:19.268
we do have to consider there's power imbalance, and that's why we need

359
00:20:19.388 --> 00:20:20.388
separate rules for police.

360
00:20:21.308 --> 00:20:24.988
Thank you, Thomas, very much for your time today and your submission.

361
00:20:25.268 --> 00:20:28.448
So thank you. We now need to head on to our next submitter-

362
00:20:28.908 --> 00:20:28.918
Thank you

363
00:20:28.918 --> 00:20:31.168
... also by Zoom. Thank you, Thomas.

364
00:20:31.828 --> 00:20:34.928
The New Zealand Law Society, and I think we may have

365
00:20:35.288 --> 00:20:38.568
Juliet Philpott and Nick Chisnell.

366
00:20:39.148 --> 00:20:42.328
Welcome. You have 10 minutes with us today. Thank you.

367
00:20:42.948 --> 00:20:45.728
Yes. Tena koutou katoa. I'm Nick Chisnell KC.

368
00:20:45.828 --> 00:20:49.517
I'm the convener of the Law Society's Criminal Law Committee, and I'm

369
00:20:49.608 --> 00:20:53.108
joined by Juliet Philpott, who's a member of the Human Rights and

370
00:20:53.188 --> 00:20:54.188
Privacy Committee.

371
00:20:55.268 --> 00:20:59.068
I intend to make some preliminary comments before asking Juliet to address you

372
00:20:59.128 --> 00:21:02.918
on Part 1 of the bill. I'll then briefly address Part 2 before

373
00:21:03.008 --> 00:21:05.628
we answer any questions that the committee may have for us.

374
00:21:05.808 --> 00:21:07.068
Thank you.

375
00:21:07.088 --> 00:21:11.038
My starting point is that the Law Society joins the Privacy Commissioner and others

376
00:21:11.088 --> 00:21:14.588
who have expressed deep concerns about the significant proposed

377
00:21:14.608 --> 00:21:18.568
expansion to police intelligence gathering powers in Part 1 of

378
00:21:18.608 --> 00:21:21.588
the bill. For Part 2, we query the

379
00:21:21.668 --> 00:21:25.548
justification for and workability of the proposed new powers

380
00:21:25.568 --> 00:21:29.327
to enforce the temporary closure of publicly accessible areas.

381
00:21:30.248 --> 00:21:33.548
If the bill was to proceed, we'd invite greater safeguards

382
00:21:34.228 --> 00:21:37.968
be put in place. So simply put, the Law Society does not

383
00:21:38.008 --> 00:21:40.688
consider that the bill should pass in its current form.

384
00:21:41.408 --> 00:21:44.568
The policy justifications for the extensions that the bill

385
00:21:45.248 --> 00:21:48.968
proposes to law enforcement powers are questionable and have not been

386
00:21:49.008 --> 00:21:50.568
sufficiently articulated.

387
00:21:51.488 --> 00:21:55.268
The lack of public consultation has produced a set of proposals

388
00:21:55.628 --> 00:21:59.327
that risk overreach and which are incompatible with settled privacy

389
00:21:59.408 --> 00:22:01.208
principles and freedom of expression.

390
00:22:02.148 --> 00:22:06.128
In our submission, if enacted, the bill will create real difficulties

391
00:22:06.168 --> 00:22:10.028
in application for police officers tasked with using its powers.

392
00:22:10.548 --> 00:22:14.468
Inevitably, litigation will ensue because the bill does not clarify

393
00:22:14.488 --> 00:22:14.868
the law.

394
00:22:15.888 --> 00:22:19.208
There is a real likelihood that Māori and Pasifika communities will be

395
00:22:19.248 --> 00:22:23.228
disproportionately affected by what is a virtually unfettered power

396
00:22:23.368 --> 00:22:26.288
to photograph and record for information gathering.

397
00:22:27.588 --> 00:22:31.048
The bill's intelligence gathering powers will have a far greater

398
00:22:31.088 --> 00:22:35.048
impact on the privacy interests of the community at large than any

399
00:22:35.108 --> 00:22:39.008
other kind of information gathering power currently available to

400
00:22:39.068 --> 00:22:42.948
law enforcement agencies, and it stands in stark contrast,

401
00:22:43.028 --> 00:22:46.068
in our view, to the careful approach that was taken to the

402
00:22:46.088 --> 00:22:49.228
enactment of the Search and Surveillance Act through

403
00:22:49.288 --> 00:22:53.078
consultation and routine statutory reviews, which in

404
00:22:53.168 --> 00:22:55.468
our view reflects what ought to happen here.

405
00:22:56.068 --> 00:23:00.008
Similarly, the approach taken in the bill starkly contrasts with the

406
00:23:00.048 --> 00:23:03.828
Criminal Investigations Samples Act, which carefully

407
00:23:03.848 --> 00:23:07.428
prescribes the taking and storage of DNA profiles,

408
00:23:07.848 --> 00:23:11.368
and that Act's fitness for purpose was recently considered by the Law

409
00:23:11.468 --> 00:23:15.328
Commission. It's deeply concerning to us that the bill

410
00:23:15.388 --> 00:23:19.248
contains no similar controls for the storage and retention

411
00:23:19.308 --> 00:23:23.208
of personal information. So with those comments in mind, I'll now hand over to

412
00:23:23.248 --> 00:23:24.678
Juliet to address you on Part 1.

413
00:23:25.568 --> 00:23:26.688
Thank you.

414
00:23:26.728 --> 00:23:30.648
Tena koutou katoa. As you've seen, the Law Society has made a range

415
00:23:30.688 --> 00:23:34.468
of specific points about Part 1 of the bill, and I'm going to focus on two of

416
00:23:34.528 --> 00:23:38.308
those today. The first is to emphasize our

417
00:23:38.348 --> 00:23:42.088
view that there are insufficient safeguards in either the bill or the Privacy Act

418
00:23:42.108 --> 00:23:45.768
to mitigate privacy risk caused by the expanded intelligence

419
00:23:45.808 --> 00:23:48.178
gathering powers that the bill would give to police.

420
00:23:48.968 --> 00:23:52.928
And I suggest this can be seen in two specific mechanisms that are proposed by the

421
00:23:52.968 --> 00:23:56.748
bill. The first is proposed Clause

422
00:23:56.908 --> 00:24:00.808
45C, which gives the police very broad powers to collect

423
00:24:00.848 --> 00:24:04.588
intelligence on private property without a warrant, and

424
00:24:04.628 --> 00:24:08.188
regardless of whether the intelligence being collected has any connection to the

425
00:24:08.228 --> 00:24:11.188
reason that the police are on the property in the first place.

426
00:24:12.148 --> 00:24:16.048
No specific safeguards are provided in the bill itself, and it

427
00:24:16.088 --> 00:24:20.008
is unclear what the justification for these provisions are, given both the Tamifuna

428
00:24:20.048 --> 00:24:23.908
decision and the IPCAOPC report involved images

429
00:24:23.948 --> 00:24:25.098
taken in public.

430
00:24:25.937 --> 00:24:29.488
The clause, as drafted, amounts to a significant imposition on

431
00:24:29.528 --> 00:24:32.498
individual privacy on private property,

432
00:24:32.908 --> 00:24:36.548
and the Law Society believes that the development of such a proposal

433
00:24:36.568 --> 00:24:40.518
requires clear justification, appropriate safeguards, and specific and

434
00:24:40.668 --> 00:24:42.168
adequate public consultation.

435
00:24:43.608 --> 00:24:46.468
The second mechanism that I

436
00:24:47.508 --> 00:24:48.048
believe

437
00:24:49.168 --> 00:24:52.488
suggests that there are insufficient safeguards is the provisions that enable

438
00:24:52.528 --> 00:24:55.628
collection of personal information for intelligence purposes in public.

439
00:24:56.628 --> 00:25:00.448
If passed, the bill enables information collection for any lawful purpose connected

440
00:25:00.488 --> 00:25:02.568
with a function or activity of the police.

441
00:25:03.368 --> 00:25:07.308
The safeguard and information privacy principle one in the Privacy Act,

442
00:25:07.348 --> 00:25:10.848
which says that police may only collect personal information that is necessary for

443
00:25:10.888 --> 00:25:13.428
a lawful purpose, will no longer apply.

444
00:25:14.188 --> 00:25:17.708
And in addition, as you're aware, the bill provides that police can collect

445
00:25:17.748 --> 00:25:21.648
intelligence data not only if it will support a police function at the time of

446
00:25:21.688 --> 00:25:25.358
collection, but also if it may support a police

447
00:25:25.488 --> 00:25:27.098
function or activity in future.

448
00:25:28.028 --> 00:25:31.918
This is expressed as a limitation on the collection of intelligence, but

449
00:25:32.088 --> 00:25:35.298
we suggest that this future-looking, highly permissive limitation will

450
00:25:35.308 --> 00:25:39.008
provide only limited protection, in particular, combined with the

451
00:25:39.028 --> 00:25:41.108
removal of the necessity requirement.

452
00:25:42.648 --> 00:25:45.548
Although the expressed intention is that the Privacy Act will continue to provide

453
00:25:45.568 --> 00:25:49.508
protection, as you know, the concept of the purpose of collection

454
00:25:49.528 --> 00:25:52.888
of information underpins most of the key information privacy principles in the

455
00:25:52.908 --> 00:25:56.828
Privacy Act. Given the permissive nature of both provisions in the bill

456
00:25:56.868 --> 00:26:00.108
that I've referred to, and the fact that these provisions will supersede the

457
00:26:00.128 --> 00:26:03.968
information privacy principles, there is a concern that any protection

458
00:26:04.008 --> 00:26:06.828
given by the Privacy Act itself would not be adequate.

459
00:26:09.108 --> 00:26:11.498
The second point I want to emphasize in the time we have

460
00:26:12.328 --> 00:26:14.808
relates to the clarity of the drafting of the provisions.

461
00:26:15.398 --> 00:26:19.368
The departmental disclosure statement explains that the bill is intended

462
00:26:19.448 --> 00:26:22.808
to address uncertainty created by the Supreme Court in Tamifuna,

463
00:26:23.568 --> 00:26:26.848
but the Law Society is concerned that the provisions themselves are drafted in a

464
00:26:26.888 --> 00:26:30.288
way that may create rather than mitigate

465
00:26:30.568 --> 00:26:31.288
uncertainty.

466
00:26:32.148 --> 00:26:34.748
An example is the provision permitting collection of information for an

467
00:26:34.788 --> 00:26:37.438
intelligence purpose connected with a function or activity of the police.

468
00:26:38.088 --> 00:26:41.797
As you know, the police's functions are listed in Section 9 of the Policing

469
00:26:41.908 --> 00:26:45.468
Act, but neither the word "activity" nor the phrase "intelligence purpose" are

470
00:26:45.508 --> 00:26:48.988
defined anywhere. Clarity around the scope of this provision is

471
00:26:49.028 --> 00:26:52.237
essential in our view, and that's not only to ensure

472
00:26:52.668 --> 00:26:56.438
there's clarity about the impact on individual privacy rights,

473
00:26:56.548 --> 00:27:00.517
but crucially to make sure that frontline police staff understand the

474
00:27:00.517 --> 00:27:03.848
limits of their authority to collect information before collection occurs.

475
00:27:04.448 --> 00:27:07.048
And we recommend at a minimum that these terms are clarified.

476
00:27:08.108 --> 00:27:11.248
Those are the two points I wanted to reiterate in the time available.

477
00:27:11.408 --> 00:27:14.368
I will just pass back to Nick to speak to you briefly about part two.

478
00:27:15.148 --> 00:27:15.448
Thank you.

479
00:27:16.048 --> 00:27:19.808
Thanks, Juliet. The Law Society's main concern is that

480
00:27:21.148 --> 00:27:24.548
whilst part two's framed towards road

481
00:27:24.628 --> 00:27:28.408
policing, has the potential application that goes well beyond that

482
00:27:28.488 --> 00:27:31.568
to protest, which of course is likely to make it

483
00:27:31.608 --> 00:27:35.408
contentious. And one thing I will say

484
00:27:35.508 --> 00:27:39.268
is that what we have is essentially a continuation of a

485
00:27:39.308 --> 00:27:42.728
power that's been there in some shape or form for nearly five decades.

486
00:27:43.328 --> 00:27:46.888
But now's the time to hit pause and to actually

487
00:27:46.968 --> 00:27:50.828
consider the rights implications of this provision, which

488
00:27:50.868 --> 00:27:54.768
is another reason why we say that alongside part

489
00:27:54.828 --> 00:27:58.108
one, there needs to be some proper consultation with it.

