1137
01:03:57.452 --> 01:04:01.432
I think it is important to recognize why protections against unreasonable

1138
01:04:01.532 --> 01:04:04.872
search and surveillance exist in the first place.

1139
01:04:04.892 --> 01:04:07.762
They are not simply technical legal limits on policing.

1140
01:04:08.312 --> 01:04:12.081
They exist to preserve the balance between state power and

1141
01:04:12.212 --> 01:04:14.592
individual freedom in a democratic society.

1142
01:04:16.272 --> 01:04:20.112
In Tamifuna, the Supreme Court was concerned about

1143
01:04:20.132 --> 01:04:23.872
broad intelligence gathering powers untethered from a

1144
01:04:23.892 --> 01:04:27.622
specific investigation. This bill moves further toward that

1145
01:04:27.652 --> 01:04:31.372
model by allowing information to be collected for broad, lawful

1146
01:04:31.412 --> 01:04:35.132
purposes, based largely on what an officer considers

1147
01:04:35.212 --> 01:04:35.592
useful.

1148
01:04:36.652 --> 01:04:40.472
The concern here is not simply that these powers are broad, but how they

1149
01:04:40.532 --> 01:04:44.432
may gradually change everyday interactions between individuals and

1150
01:04:44.472 --> 01:04:45.052
the state.

1151
01:04:45.932 --> 01:04:49.832
In practice, ordinary people who are not suspected of wrongdoing may still

1152
01:04:49.852 --> 01:04:53.152
be recorded and have information retained by police.

1153
01:04:53.972 --> 01:04:57.792
Over time, when surveillance becomes routine rather than exceptional,

1154
01:04:58.372 --> 01:05:02.292
there is a risk that people begin to expect monitoring as

1155
01:05:02.432 --> 01:05:06.072
a normal part of public life. That matters

1156
01:05:06.112 --> 01:05:09.972
because public freedom in a democratic society depends not only on

1157
01:05:10.012 --> 01:05:13.832
rights existing formally, but on people feeling able to participate

1158
01:05:14.492 --> 01:05:18.112
openly in public life without unnecessary state

1159
01:05:18.212 --> 01:05:21.592
intrusion. Broad discretionary powers can also

1160
01:05:21.692 --> 01:05:25.372
undermine trust in policing if their use

1161
01:05:25.492 --> 01:05:28.532
appears inconsistent or uneven.

1162
01:05:29.472 --> 01:05:33.312
Ultimately, the concern is about ensuring that expanded police powers

1163
01:05:33.432 --> 01:05:37.361
remain proportionate, clearly limited, and consistent with

1164
01:05:37.412 --> 01:05:40.792
the values Section 21 NZBORA exists to protect.

